==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|bestowen}}, {{m|enm|bistowen}}, equivalent to {{prefix|be|t1=on, over, about|stow|t2=to put something away|lang=en}}. Cognate to Dutch {{m|nl|bestoiwen}}, {{m|nl|bestuwen}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|/bɪˈstoʊ/|lang=en}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/bɪˈstəʊ/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|əʊ|lang=en}}
* {{hyph|lang=en|be|stow}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[lay up]] in store; [[deposit]] for safe keeping; [[stow]]; [[place]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1599|title=Hamlet|author=William Shakespeare|page=|ISBN=|passage=Her father and myself, ⟨lawful espials,⟩ ⟨Will⟩ so '''bestow''' ourselves that, seeing unseen, We may of their encounter frankly judge And gather by him, as he is behaved, If 't be th' affliction of his love or no That thus he suffers for.}}
#* '''1611''', King James Bible, Luke 12:17:
#*: And he thought within himself, saying, What shall I do, because I have no room where to '''bestow''' my fruits.
#* '''1977''', {{w|J.R.R. Tolkien}}, ''{{w|Of the Rings of Power}}'', HarperCollins, page 358:
#*: Of the Three Rings that the Elves had preserved unsullied no open word was ever spoken among the Wise, and few even of the Eldar knew where they were '''bestowed'''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To lodge, or find quarters for; provide with accommodation.
#* {{quote-text|lang=en|year=1838|author={{w|Ben Jonson}}|title=The works of Ben Jonson|passage=Well, my masters, I'll leave him with you; now I see him '''bestowed''', I'll go look for my goods, and Numps.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[dispose]] of.
#* '''1615-17''', {{w|Thomas Middleton}} et al., ''{{w|The Widow (play)|The Widow}}'', in ''The Ancient British drama'', edited by Robert Dodsley, Sir Walter Scott, published 1810:
#*: Here are blank warrants of all dispositions; give me but the name and nature of your malefactor, and I'll '''bestow''' him according to his merits.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1645-46|title=Fast sermons to Parliament|page=129|ISBN=|passage=Ye seek your selves in you praiers, Ye ask that ye may consume it upon your lusts; you would have the blessings of God to '''bestow''' them upon your pleasures, not to do his pleasure.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1734|title=The Gentleman's Magazine, Or, Monthly Intelligencer - Volume 4|author=|page=505|ISBN=|passage=Richmond, thy purling streams and pleasing shades, Might claim the chorus of Aonian maids ; Where e'en Apollo might his hours '''bestow''', By turns employ his lyre, by turns his bow, Where all the pleasures dwell, which poets feign On fair Arcadia's fields or Tempe's plain.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[give]]; [[confer]]; [[impart]] gratuitously; [[present]] something to someone or something, especially as a [[gift]] or [[honour]].
#: ''Medals were '''bestowed''' on the winning team.''
#* '''1831''', {{w|Mary Shelley}}, ''[[s:Frankenstein|Frankenstein]]''
#*: Soft tears again bedewed my cheeks, and I even raised my humid eyes with thankfulness towards the blessed sun which '''bestowed''' such joy upon me.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1873|title=The Wooing O'T: A Novel|author=Mrs. Alexander|page=250|ISBN=|passage=Sometimes I am caught by a delightful fragment in a magazine, and blaze up into the fiercest interest, '''bestow''' maledictions on the delay which the intervening month creates, but am burnt out by the time it expires, and so lose the thread.}}
#* '''2008''', [[w:J. D. Frazer|Illiad]], ''Userfriendly.org'', “[http://ars.userfriendly.org/cartoons/?id=20080928 The Large Hadron Collider Game]”
#*: CERN '''bestows''' slush fund on the LHC. Take all pennies from the CERN space.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give in [[marriage]].
#* '''1590-92''', William Shakespeare, ''The Taming of the Shrew, Act 1, Scene 1, lines 50-51'':
#*: That is not to '''bestow''' my youngest daughter/ before I have a husband for the elder.
#* {{quote-journal|lang=en|passage=I could have '''bestowed''' her upon a fine gentleman.|journal=The Tatler|author=Joseph Addison|issue=75|year=1709}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[apply]]; make use of; [[use]]; [[employ]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1734|title=The Gentleman's Magazine, Or, Monthly Intelligencer - Volume 4|author=|page=|ISBN=|passage=Here 'tis worth while to '''bestow''' a few more Reflections upon that extraordinary Piece of barbarous Cruelty against their Country under the Character of Rufinus.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1850|title=Half Hours with the Best Authors|author=Charles Knight & ‎John Leighton|page=290|ISBN=|passage=All the void time that is between the hours of work, sleep, and meat, that they be suffered to '''bestow''' every man as he liketh best himself.}}
#* '''1887''', John Marston, Arthur Henry Bullen, ''The Works of John Marston'':
#*: [...] I determine to '''bestow''' Some time in learning languages abroad; [...]
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[behave]] or [[deport]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1597|title=Henry IV, part 1|author=William Shakespeare|page=|ISBN=|passage=How might we see Falstaff '''bestow''' himself to-night in his true colours?}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1750|title=The Works of Mr. Francis Beaumont, and Mr. John Fletcher|author=Francis Beaumont, ‎John Fletcher, ‎& Mr. Theobald (Lewis)|page=448|ISBN=|passage=By this light, Sir, (But that I never will '''bestow''' myself But to your liking) if she now would have me, I now would marry her.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1883|title=The Anatomy of Melancholy|author=Robert Burton|page=|ISBN=|passage=And thence it comes to pass, that in city and country so many grievances of body and mind, and this feral disease of melancholy so frequently rageth, and now domineers almost all over Europe amongst our great ones. They know not how to spend their time (disports excepted, which are all their business), what to do, or otherwise how to '''bestow''' themselves ; like our modern Frenchmen, that had rather lose a pound of blood in a single combat, than a drop of sweat in any honest labour.}}

